Introduction¶

The CIFAR-10 dataset consits of 60,000 color images of size 32 x 32 collected by by Krizhevsky, Nair, and Hinton. The dataset has 10 classes, each class having 6,000 images which is divided in to two groups:

  • Training: 50,000 images
  • Testing: 10,000 images

The classes are completely mutually exclusive. There is no overlap between automobiles and trucks. "Automobile" includes sedans, SUVs, things of that sort. "Truck" includes only big trucks. Neither includes pickup trucks.

Johannes Schade (5564109)

Yolanda Seifert (5477060)

David Bauer (5398867)

All questions answered here¶

The first simple convnet overfitted very much, having a near 100% accuracy on the training set but only 39% on the test set, which is still a lot better than chance.

With the first larger convnet we have less good results with the accuracy not outperforming chance. This could be explained by the much larger size of the convnet, a lot more features need to be learnt and the net doesn't manage to improve. Always predicting the same class ensures a 10% success rate

Adding Batch Normalization improves our net by alot jumping to ca. 48%, still overfitted strongly though.

Dropout Layers can isolate certain neurons to make them learn independently from others improving our accuracy slightly but greatly reducing overfitting, the accuracy on the test set is reduced to 70% instead of close to 100%

Image Augmentation adds randomness to the training data which will reduce overfitting aswell as teaching features independently of the orientation of an image. In our case the improvement was minimal and we observed a reduction of accuracy and slightly more overfitting. Tuning the randomness of the transformations might help.

Plots¶

The first and second plots don't look to have a lot of structure, but the spread of the data is less in the simple model, maybe meaning there is some more structure added to the distribution of classes.

In the third there is obvious structure, some of the data points seam to mass in the bottom where they are less differentiated but certain labels are clearly seperated from the rest and some classes that "should" have common features (cars and trucks/ cats and dogs) tend to overlap.

# Code for loading the data 
(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = tf.keras.datasets.cifar10.load_data()
# Classes (are given)
classes = np.array(['airplane', 'automobile', 'bird', 'cat', 'deer', 'dog', 'frog', 'horse', 'ship', 'truck'])

# Code for printing the shape of your training set 
print(f'# x_train = {x_train.shape}, # y_train = {y_train.shape}')

# Code for rescaling the images
def preprocess_images(x):
    return x.astype('float32')/255.
xtrain = preprocess_images(x_train)

# Code for splitting the data into train/val/test set 
Xtrain_, Xrest_, Ytrain, Yrest_ = train_test_split(xtrain, y_train, train_size=10000)
Xval_, Xrest_, Yval, Yrest_ = train_test_split(Xrest_, Yrest_, train_size=1000)
Xtest_, Xrest_, Ytest, Yrest_ = train_test_split(Xrest_, Yrest_, train_size=1000)

# Code for printing the # of samples in each class 
def count_samples(ls):
    distribution = np.zeros(10)
    for i in ls:
        distribution[i] += 1
    return distribution


train_distribution = count_samples(Ytrain)
test_distribution = count_samples(Ytest)

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15,3))
ax1.bar(classes,  train_distribution, width=0.5) 
ax2.bar(classes,  test_distribution, width=0.5)

std_train = np.std(Xtrain_)

mean_test = np.mean(Xtest_)
std_test = np.std(Xtest_)

print("train : ", 'mean', mean_train, 'std', std_train)

# Code for training on Cifar-10
def cifar10_clf(input_shape=(32,32,3), n_classes=10):
    inx = Input(input_shape)
    x = layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu')(inx)
    x = layers.Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3, 3), strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu')(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(128, kernel_size=(3, 3), strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu')(x)
    x = layers.Flatten()(x)
    x = layers.Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
    x = layers.Dense(n_classes)(x)
    return Model(inx, x)

clf_cifar10 = cifar10_clf()
clf_cifar10.summary()

# select loss function and optimizer
loss = losses.CategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True)
opt = optimizers.Nadam(learning_rate=1e-2)
clf_cifar10.compile(loss=loss, optimizer=opt, metrics=['accuracy'])

# preprocess data: scaling of images, one-hot encoding of labels
def preprocess_tf(x, y):
    return x, tf.one_hot(y, depth=10, axis=-1)

trainset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((Xtrain_, Ytrain.flatten())).shuffle(Xtrain_.shape[0]).batch(256).map(preprocess_tf)
valset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((Xval_, Yval.flatten())).batch(1000).map(preprocess_tf)

# callback for saving model
MdlCpt = callbacks.ModelCheckpoint('cpt/convnet_cifar10_1', save_best_only=True)

hist = clf_cifar10.fit(trainset, validation_data=valset, epochs=100, callbacks=[MdlCpt])

Implement a NN with the following structure:

  • Input layer -> Conv block 0 -> Conv block 1 -> Conv block 2 -> Conv block 3 -> Dense layer -> Output layer

  • Conv block 0: Conv2D(32, (3,3)) -> Conv2D(32, (3,3))

  • Conv block 1: Conv2D(64, (3,3)) -> Conv2D(32, (3,3))

  • Conv block 2: Conv2D(128, (3,3)) -> Conv2D(32, (3,3))

  • Conv block 3: Conv2D(128, (3,3)) -> Conv2D(32, (3,3))

  • Padding is always 'same', kernel_initializer is 'he_uniform', and activation function is 'relu'

  • Dense layer: layers.Flatten() -> layers.Dense(512, activation='relu')

  • Output layer: layers.Dense(10)

  • Train this model on the cifar-10 data for 100 epochs and make predictions on the test data

  • Create a checkpoint to save the best model (see ModelCheckpoint)

  • Print the classification report and confusion matrix

  • Plot training loss vs. validation loss

  • Plot Training accuracy vs. validation accuracy

  • Did the results improve in comparison to the last model?

# Code for model 2 

initializer = tf.keras.initializers.HeUniform(seed=1)


def conv_block (in_size, out_size, x) :
  x = layers.Conv2D(in_size, kernel_size=(3, 3), strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initializer)(x)
  return layers.Conv2D(out_size, kernel_size=(3, 3), strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initializer)(x)


def model2(input_shape=(32,32,3), n_classes=10) :
  inx = Input(input_shape)
  
  x = conv_block(32, 32, inx)
  x = conv_block(64,32, x)
  x = conv_block(128,32, x)
  x = conv_block(128,32, x)

  x = layers.Flatten()(x)

  x = layers.Dense(512, activation='relu')(x)
  x = layers.Dense(n_classes)(x)
  return Model(inx, x)


model_2 = model2()
model_2.summary()

# Code for model 3


def conv_block_2 (in_size, out_size, x) :
  x = layers.Conv2D(in_size, kernel_size=(3, 3), strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initializer)(x)
  x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
  x = layers.Conv2D(out_size, kernel_size=(3, 3), strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initializer)(x)
  return layers.BatchNormalization()(x)

def model3(input_shape=(32,32,3), n_classes=10) :
  inx = Input(input_shape)
  
  x = conv_block_2(32, 32, inx)
  x = conv_block_2(64,32, x)
  x = conv_block_2(128,32, x)
  x = conv_block_2(128,32, x)

  x = layers.Flatten()(x)

  x = layers.Dense(512, activation='relu')(x)
  x = layers.Dense(n_classes)(x)
  return Model(inx, x)

model_3 = model3()
model_3.summary()

model_3.compile(loss=loss, optimizer=opt, metrics=['accuracy'])

# Code for model 4


def conv_block_3 (in_size, out_size, x, drop_rate) :
  x = layers.Conv2D(in_size, kernel_size=(3, 3), strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initializer)(x)
  x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
  x = layers.Conv2D(out_size, kernel_size=(3, 3), strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initializer)(x)
  x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
  return layers.Dropout(drop_rate)(x)

def model4(input_shape=(32,32,3), n_classes=10) :
  inx = Input(input_shape)
  
  x = conv_block_3(32, 32, inx, 0.1)
  x = conv_block_3(64,32, x, 0.2)
  x = conv_block_3(128,32, x, 0.3)
  x = conv_block_3(128,32, x, 0.4)

  x = layers.Flatten()(x)

  x = layers.Dense(512, activation='relu')(x)
  x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
  x = layers.Dense(n_classes)(x)

  return Model(inx, x)


model_4 = model4()

# Code for image augmentation + the rest of the tasks mentioned above
def model5(input_shape=(32,32,3), n_classes=10) :
  inx = Input(input_shape)
    # image augmentation
  x = layers.RandomFlip()(inx)
  x = layers.RandomRotation(0.2)(x)
  x = layers.RandomTranslation(0.2,0.2)(x)

  x = conv_block_3(32, 32, inx, 0.1)
  x = conv_block_3(64,32, x, 0.2)
  x = conv_block_3(128,32, x, 0.3)
  x = conv_block_3(128,32, x, 0.4)

  x = layers.Flatten()(x)

  x = layers.Dense(512, activation='relu')(x)
  x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
  x = layers.Dense(n_classes)(x)

  return Model(inx, x)

# Code for the three different 3D scatter plots 

def make_plot (x, y) :
  pca = PCA(n_components=3)
  pc_fit = pca.fit_transform(x, y)

  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
  ax = fig.add_subplot(projection='3d')

  print(pc_fit.shape)

  
  #ax.scatter(pc_fit[:,0], pc_fit[:,1], pc_fit[:,2], y[:])
  for l in np.unique(y):
    xax = np.take(pc_fit, np.where(y == l), axis=0)
    ax.scatter(xax[0, :, 0], xax[0, :, 1], xax[0, :, 2], label=classes[l])


  ax.set_xlabel("pc1", fontsize=14)
  ax.set_ylabel("pc2", fontsize=14)
  ax.set_zlabel("pc3", fontsize=14)

  ax.legend()
  plt.show()
